---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'About | wrongfuldeathcalc.com';
const description = 'About wrongfuldeathcalc.com — who we are, why we built a wrongful death calculator, and our approach to a sensitive topic.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>About wrongfuldeathcalc.com</h1>

  <p>wrongfuldeathcalc.com is a free, ad-supported reference site for families navigating the legal aftermath of a wrongful death. We are not a law firm and do not take cases. Our editorial content isn't for sale — no attorney pays for coverage or a favorable mention in our guides. Separately, the site includes an optional case-review form that connects families who want their situation evaluated with attorneys; that's a disclosed paid referral, not editorial content, and using it is always optional (see "How we make money" below and our <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a>). We exist to give survivors a starting framework for understanding what a wrongful death claim might be worth so they can have a more informed first conversation with an attorney.</p>

  <h2>Why this site exists</h2>
  <p>The legal landscape around wrongful death is harder to navigate than ordinary personal injury. The damages categories are different. The people eligible to file vary by state. Statutes of limitations are tighter &mdash; in some states as short as one year. And the conversations are happening at a moment when survivors are in active grief and least equipped to absorb procedural detail.</p>
  <p>The single most common harm we see is families who delay calling an attorney until critical evidence has been lost, statutes of limitations have shortened, or an insurance company has secured a settlement release for far less than the case was worth. We built this site to give survivors enough framework to act sooner and ask the right questions.</p>

  <h2>How we approach a sensitive topic</h2>
  <p>This is not a topic where we want to come across as transactional. At the same time, the people who land here are trying to make decisions about real dollar amounts, often under time pressure. We try to write plainly and informatively without either minimizing the loss or being mawkish about it. The calculator does what calculators do; the surrounding text tries to be useful.</p>
  <p>If you're reading this in the immediate aftermath of a death, the most important thing is to find an attorney who handles wrongful death cases in your state. State bar lawyer referral services are a starting point. The American Association for Justice and state trial lawyer associations also maintain referral resources.</p>

  <h2>Who runs the site</h2>
  <p>The Click Lab operates a portfolio of legal calculator reference sites. This one is led editorially by a paralegal with wrongful death and probate experience, with a contributing writer on survivor and estate damages. Credentials and coverage areas are on the <a href="/editorial">editorial page</a>.</p>

  <h2>How we make money</h2>
  <p>Display advertising via Google AdSense. No sponsored content or paid placements in our editorial content. We also offer an optional case-review form on the homepage: if you submit it, your information is shared with attorneys who may compensate The Click Lab Agency LLC for the referral. That's a disclosed advertising product, separate from our editorial content, and using it is always optional. Our <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a> covers data practices, including exactly what's shared if you use that form.</p>

  <h2>What we will and won't do</h2>
  <p>We <strong>will</strong> explain how wrongful death damages are calculated, walk through who has standing to bring a claim in your state, identify the statute of limitations that applies to your situation, and help you understand the questions to ask the attorney you eventually hire.</p>
  <p>We <strong>won't</strong> represent your family or pretend a calculator output is a binding case valuation. If you choose to submit the case-review form, see the privacy policy for what happens to your information — we don't share anything unless you submit that form yourself.</p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>If you find a factual error or have a content suggestion, the <a href="/contact">contact page</a> tells you how to reach the editor.</p>
</BaseLayout>
